%N A341362 a(n) begins the first sequence of n consecutive positive integers with the same h-value and the same d-value in the Collatz (or '3x + 1') problem.
%C A341362 The Collatz function is as follows: F(x) = x/2 if x is even, otherwise F(x) = 3*x+1.
%C A341362 It is conjectured that starting from any number, and repeatedly applying the function on its previous result, we will always reach 1.
%C A341362 The d-value (or flight duration, A006577) is the number of steps needed to reach 1.  The h-value (or flight height, A025586) is the maximum of the number's trajectory.
%H A341362 Guo-Gang Gao, <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0012-365X(93)90240-T">On consecutive numbers of the same height in the Collatz problem</a>, Discrete Mathematics, Volume 112, pages 261-267, 1993.
%e A341362 a(3) = 108 because 108, 109 and 110 have same d-value (113) and same h-value (9232).
%e A341362 And 108 is the smallest number starting such sequence of 3 consecutive positive integers with same d-value and same h-value.
